{
  "text": "One method for dealing with vast state spaces is to use function learning as a mechanism for generalizing prior experience to unobserved states [CITATION_1] . The function learning approach approximates a global value function over all options, including ones not experienced yet [CITATION_2] . This allows for generalization to vast and potentially infinite state spaces, based on a small number of observations. Additionally, function learning scales to problems with complex sequential dynamics and has been used in tandem with restricted search methods, such as Monte Carlo sampling, for navigating intractably large search trees [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . While restricted search methods have been proposed as models of human reinforcement learning in planning tasks [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , here we focus on situations in which a rich model of environmental structure supports learning and generalization [CITATION_7] .",
  "correct_citation": {
